Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) is a type of attack where malicious code is injected into the victim's browser, causing them to inadvertently perform actions on a website without their knowledge or consent. To prevent CSRF attacks in ASP.NET, you can use the Same-Origin Policy by checking the Referer header in the incoming requests.

The Same-Origin Policy is a browser security feature that prevents scripts loaded from one origin to access resources on another origin. It restricts requests from scripts running in a web page to request resources from another domain or port. This policy can be used to check the HTTP Referer header to ensure that requests are coming from a trusted source.

To implement Same-Origin Policy to prevent CSRF attacks in ASP.NET, you can do the following:

1. Identify and validate HTTP Referer header:
In your ASP.NET application, you can identify requests sent from the client with a Referer header. You can check the value of the HTTP Referer header in the incoming requests and validate that the Referer is from the same domain as the application. 

```csharp
string incomingReferer = HttpContext.Current.Request.UrlReferrer.DnsSafeHost;
if (incomingReferer != "example.com")
{
     // Request is not from the same domain, do not process the request
}
```

This code snippet retrieves the value of the HTTP Referer header from the incoming request and checks that the Referer domain is the same as the current domain. 

2. Use Anti-forgery tokens:
As mentioned earlier, you can use Anti-forgery tokens to prevent CSRF attacks. You can generate and include Anti-forgery tokens in each form and request sent by the client.

```csharp
@using System.Web.Helpers
<form>
  @Html.AntiForgeryToken()
  ...
</form>
```

By using the Same-Origin Policy and Anti-forgery tokens, you can prevent CSRF attacks in your ASP.NET web application. These checks and validations can be implemented in your code, and no specific changes are required to be made in the web.config file to implement the same.

